@Jhon Krasnovskiy Electric is not the savior of engines like many think.  Yes, they have their place and yes, they are great at delivering instant acceleration.  For me, and this is not meant to bash anyone with an EV,  but I do not like the idea of having to search for a charging station, possibly wait for someone to finish using it, and then wait about an hour to recharge.  I put about 20K -30K miles on my vehicles a year, depending on where I travel to.  Charging times, at least currently, are too long for me.  Another concern is storms.  How do you charge your vehicle if the power grid is down in your area such as if a hurricane hits?  If I want to travel a great distance that is kind of remote, I can always carry an appropriate amount of fuel cans in the back of my truck.  You can't carry a bucket of electrons to carry around as extra fuel.  Anyway, EV is great for people who just stay in their local area and return home.  At least for now, not so great for long-distant travelers.  
The mention of Sun and Wind for power generation:  Sun and Wind requires a lot of real-estate to get the same amount of energy of a modest conventional power plant.  Windmills look horrible, are noisy, and kill countless numbers of birds.  Solar is very expensive and the panels that are out are certainly getting better, but efficiency still has a long way to go. 
The ICE has a lot of potential still.  With fuel cells and hydrogen power, you can create very clean-burning engines.  We just need to extract H from water or the air, not from petroleum like we currently do.  I'll end with this:  I am an all the above technology guy.  There is room and a need for all forms of energy production.  I just do not want to see the ICE rushed out of production and replaced with an inferior technology.  I want personal choice, not a government-mandated order.  Everybody chooses the vehicle that best suits their personal needs.﻿

